            <fr:title text="Vector ISA / SIMD">Vector ISA / SIMD</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><html:p><html:em>Single instruction, multiple data</html:em>. Extend the <fr:link href="/VZDH/" title="Fetch-execute loop" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/VZDH/" display-uri="VZDH" type="local">Fetch-execute loop</fr:link> so that one fetch+decode applies the same operation to a vector of operands. The fetch-decode overhead amortizes over the vector width; loop bookkeeping (increment, compare, branch) is replaced by a single vector op.</html:p><html:p>Concretely, a vector ISA adds:</html:p><html:ul><html:li>A <html:em>vector register file</html:em> — wider than scalar registers; specify the data width per element and total bits per register.</html:li>
  <html:li>Vector load/store instructions for moving contiguous chunks of memory to/from vector registers efficiently.</html:li>
  <html:li><html:em>Vector predication</html:em> (masking) — apply the op only where the mask is true, allowing data-dependent control flow without scalar branches.</html:li></html:ul><html:p>Trade-offs:</html:p><html:ul><html:li>Need the array length to be divisible by the vector width for perfect speedup; tail handling is annoying.</html:li>
  <html:li>Vector pipelines cannot do <fr:link href="/USSP/" title="Forwarding" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/USSP/" display-uri="USSP" type="local">Forwarding</fr:link> cheaply — would need <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[O(n^2)]]></fr:tex> connections to every ALU.</html:li>
  <html:li>Wider hardware vectors can be supported on narrower hardware by <fr:link href="/87GH/" title="Microarchitecture" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/87GH/" display-uri="87GH" type="local">microcoded</fr:link> decomposition; backward compatibility falls out for free.</html:li></html:ul><html:p>In practice, vector code is generated by:</html:p><html:ol><html:li>Intrinsic functions (architecture-specific C builtins).</html:li>
  <html:li>Vector data types in a language extension.</html:li>
  <html:li>External libraries (BLAS, etc.).</html:li>
  <html:li>Compiler auto-vectorization.</html:li></html:ol>
    <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors /><fr:date><fr:year>2026</fr:year><fr:month>5</fr:month><fr:day>12</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>Problem</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>Aliasing: modifying a vector you're also reading from causes a race within the operation.</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>

    <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors /><fr:date><fr:year>2026</fr:year><fr:month>5</fr:month><fr:day>12</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>Remark</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>SIMD is hardware-driven data parallelism. The GPU descendant is <fr:link href="/82U4/" title="GPU architecture and SIMT" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/82U4/" display-uri="82U4" type="local">SIMT</fr:link>, which softens many of SIMD's rigidities.</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
</fr:mainmatter>
